#session :=A session in Django keeps the user logged in by storing user data on the server. 
        ; As long as the session is active, the user does not need to log in again.

        ; ✅ What Actually Happens

        ; When a user logs in to your Django website:
        ; Django creates a session ID
        ; That session ID is stored in the browser (cookie)
        ; The session data is stored on the server
        ; As long as the session is active → user stays logged in


; 📌 Django Session Framework (Simple & Clear Notes)
; 🔹 What is a Session?
; In Django, a session is a way to store information about a user after they log in or visit your website.
; 👉 It helps Django remember the user between different pages.

; Example:

; User logs in → Django remembers them.
; User adds items to cart → Django remembers the cart.
; User fills a form → Data can be stored temporarily.

; 🔹 How Django Session Works (Simple Explanation)
; When a user visits your website, Django creates a unique session ID.
; That session ID is stored in a cookie in the user's browser.
; The actual data (cart, login info, etc.) is stored on the server, not in the browser.
; Every time the user makes a request, Django reads the session ID from the cookie and loads the data from the database.

; 👉 So:
; 🍪 Cookie → Contains only Session ID
; 🖥 Server → Stores actual session data

; 🔹 Important Point
; Django sessions are server-side stored.

; That means:
; Data is safe.
; User cannot see or modify it easily.
; Only session ID is stored in browser cookie.






